article.headline: Washington State 83, Arizona State 70
article.story: TEMPE, Ariz. (AP) -- Washington State kept its Pac-10 Tournament hopes alive and likely ended Arizona State's chances. Marcus Moore and Jeff Varem each scored 21 points as the Cougars used a second-half rally to beat the Sun Devils 83-70 Thursday night. Thomas Kelati added 14 points for Washington State (12-13, 6-9 Pac-10), which maintained its hold on eighth place in the league standings -- the cutoff point to qualify for the conference tournament. "Our defense was much better and when we got up and got them out of that zone, I felt better," said Cougars first-year coach Dick Bennett. "We ran some isolation from the side and we able to cash in there and that was probably the difference." Arizona State (10-15, 4-12) remained in the Pac-10 cellar despite Ike Diogu's 28 points. "It shocks me that we didn't play harder than we did," said Sun Devils coach Rob Evans. "We fought hard in the first half but we couldn't keep it going in the second half. We traded baskets when we should have been getting stops." The Cougars led 62-58 with 6:10 left before Moore gave his team some breathing room with a leaner off the glass and a reverse layup. Varem later added seven straight points, including a 3-point play, that put Washington State ahead 73-63 with 3:23 remaining. "I like to play matchups. That's the way I play basketball," said Varem, whose point total was one shy of his career-high set earlier this season against USC. "If I've got a little man on me and I'm quicker than him, I'll take him." Arizona State had led 41-37 at halftime behind Diogu's 24 points. He closed the half with 21 points on 7-of-10 shooting from the field. Washington State trailed 47-41 with 15:50 to play before Moore and Varem keyed a comeback. Jamal Hill finished with 14 points and Stevie Moore 10 for the Sun Devils. The 83 points were a season-high for the Cougars, who owned a 33-22 rebounding edge and generated 13 second-chance points off 12 offensive boards.
